'''Kapnobatai''' or '''capnobatae''', meaning "''those who walk on/in smoke/clouds''"<ref name=strabo/> was one of the names given to the [[Mysians]] of [[Thrace]] (modern-day Bulgaria) who practiced the dietary restriction of not consuming living things, thus living on milk and honey. The description is given by [[Strabo]] who attributes the information to [[Posidonius]].<ref name=strabo>[[Strabo]], ''{{plain link|url=http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0099.tlg001.perseus-eng1:7.3 |name=Geography}}'' VII.3.3, and note 17: literally "Smoke-treaders"</ref>

Mysians are understood as a people who originally from Asia Minor, but those living in Thrace have become confounded with the Getae, according to Strabo.<ref name=strabo/> As such, some commentators refer to them as [[Dacians|Dacian]] priesthood.<ref>{{citation|last=Ustinova |first=Yulia |author-link=Yulia Ustinova|title=Caves and the Ancient Greek Mind|publisher=OUP Oxford |year=2009|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TA4UDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA102 |page=102}}</ref>

==Cannabis==
{{Fringe section|date=January 2018}}
The interpretation that the "smoke-walkers" refer to cannabis smokers have been pushed by some authors, who think that the practice also extends to the ethnography of the [[Scythian]]s. These authors imagine that the Kapnobatai must have burned [[cannabis (drug)|cannabis]] flowers to induce a state of [[trance]].<ref name="urlThe Scythians">{{cite web | title = The Scythians | author = Chris Bennet | url = http://www.lost-civilizations.net/scythians.html}}</ref> It is believed that as cannabis slowly spread westward, these peoples were introduced to it by the ancient [[Aryan]]s, of whom in turn were introduced to it by the ancient [[Assyria]]ns, and them by the ancient [[Hindu]]s. These past cultures were some of the very first to [[smoking|smoke]] cannabis for [[recreational drug use|recreational]] and [[spirituality|spiritual]] purposes.

