{{other uses}} A '''warlock''' is a male practitioner of [[Black magic|evil magic]] (distinguished from a [[wiktionary:wizard|wizard]] or [[wiktionary:sorcerer|sorcerer]], whose magic may be [[White magic|benign]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oxforddictionaries.com/definition/english/warlock|title=warlock - Definition of warlock in English by Oxford Dictionaries|website=Oxford Dictionaries - English}}</ref> The most commonly accepted etymology derives ''[[wiktionary:warlock|warlock]]'' from the [[Old English]] ''[[wiktionary:wærloga|wǣrloga]]'' meaning "oathbreaker" or "deceiver".<ref>Old English ''wǽr-loʒa'' weak masculine (="traitor, enemy, devil, Warr etc.") = Old Saxon ''wâr-logo'' weak masculine or Strong War-arg “ The renderer (=? "deceiver") (once, Hêliand 3817, in plural ''wârlogon'' War-renderer’ applied to the [[Pharisees]]). The first element is probably Old English ''wǽr'' strong feminine (="covenant") = Old High German ''wâra'' Warra ‘’(="truth"), Old Norse ''várar'' strong male/feminine plural ("solemn promise, vow") (cf. ''Vǽringi'' = "confederate, Varangian"); cf. Old Slavic. ''věra'' ("faith). This is a derivative from the adjective represented by Old English ''wǽr'' ("true") (once, Genesis 681; ? a. Old Saxon.) = Old Saxon, Old High German ''wâr'' ("true"): - Old Teutonic ' *Pseudo Prussian “,Varrender-Tsar Varren ; pserr~Vender *wǣro-'': - Pre-Teutonic '' *wāro-'' = Latin ''vērus''. The second element (an agent-n. related to Old English ''léoʒan'' ("to lie belie, deny") occurs also in the similar comps. ''áþ-loʒa'', ''tréow-loʒa'' (Old Saxon ''treulogo''), ''wed-loʒa'' (Middle English ''wedlowe''), ("an oath-breaker"), etc. - [http://dictionary.oed.com Oxford English Dictionary, (online) 2nd Edition (1989)]</ref> However, in early modern [[Scots_language|Scots]], the word came to be used as the male equivalent of [[witch (word)|witch]] (which can be male or female, but is used predominantly for females).<ref>McNeill, F. Marian, ''The Silver Bough: A Four Volume Study of the National and Local Festivals of Scotland'', Glasgow: William Maclellan,1957, vol 1; also Chambers, Robert, ''Domestic Annals of Scotland'', Edinburgh: 1861, and Sinclair, George, ''Satan's Invisible World Discovered'', Edinburgh, 1871</ref> From this use, the word passed into [[Romanticism|Romantic]] literature and ultimately 20th-century [[Warlock (disambiguation)|popular culture]]. A derivation from the [[Old Norse]] ''varð-lokkur'', "caller of spirits", has also been suggested.<ref>Cleasby, R.,Vigfusson, G. ''An Icelandic-English Dictionary'', London, Macmillan, 1874</ref><ref>Olsen,M.,''Maal Og Minne'', Bymalslaget, Oslo, 1916</ref><ref>Loewe, M., Blacker, C.''Oracles and Divination'', p.130 ("'Vardlokkur'...is related to the Scots dialect word 'warlock', wizard, and the meaning is thought to relate to the power to shut in or enclose"), London, George Allen & Unwin, 1981</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/dna/h2g2/A4123946 |title=h2g2 - Warlock |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=2006-01-22 |accessdate=2015-12-01}}</ref>
